<subsection xml:id="subsec-application-of-scale-drawings2">
    <title>Application of scale drawings(2)</title>
    
    <p>
        In the previous section, you applied scale drawing to determine actual measurements 
        when given scale measurements. Review again if you can still attempt any question of such.
    </p>
    <p>
        In this section, you will apply scale drawing to determine the scale measurements when given 
        actual measurement. You are required to identify the original length of a figure which is already drawn to scale.
    </p>
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Work in pairs.}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{What you require:}</m> A ruler and a piece of string.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Take a picture of your choice, determine the linear scale of the picture and represent it on piece of paper.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Discus the following question with your partner.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="(a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    What is the scale of the chosen picture in statment form? 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Using a piece of string and a ruler, measure the length of the picture 
                                    in centimetres.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Use the scale to determine the actual length of the picture.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Discuss your work with other learners in class.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A model of an elephant at the entrance of a national park 
                was made using a scale of <m>1\,cm</m> represents <m>0.25\,m</m>. The length of a certain part 
                of the elephant is <m>140\,cm.</m> Calculate the length of the part of the model.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since the given scale relates centimeters on the model to 
                meters on the actual elephant, we first convert the actual length from cm to meters:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 1 \,m= \amp 100\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow> 140 \,cm= ​\amp \frac{140}{100}</mrow>
                    <mrow>  =\amp 1.4 \,m</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The given scale states that:
            </p>
            <p>
               <m> 1 \,cm </m> on model <m>=0.25 \,m </m> on actual elephant
            </p>
            <p>
                To find the length of the part on the model, we set up the proportion:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 1 \,cm =\amp 0.25 \,m</mrow>
                    <mrow> ?=\amp 1.4 \,m</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{ 1.4 \,m \times 1 \,cm}{0.25 \,m} </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp  5.6 \,cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore,
            </p>
            <p>
                The length of the part of the model is <m>{\color{blue} 5.6 cm.}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A model of a giraffe at the entrance of a wildlife sanctuary was made using a scale where <m>1 \,cm </m> on the model represents <m>0.5\, m </m> in real life. 
                The actual height of the giraffe is 300 cm. Calculate the height of the giraffe model.

                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The given information are as shown.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Scale: 1 cm on the model represents <m>0.5\, m </m>in real life.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Actual height of the giraffe: <m>300 \,cm.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We need to find the height of the giraffe model.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since the scale is given in meters, we first convert 300 cm to meters:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 1 \,m= \amp 100\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow> 300\,cm= ​\amp \frac{300}{100}</mrow>
                    <mrow>  =\amp 3\,m</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The scale states that:
            </p>
            <p>
               <m> 1 \,cm </m> on model <m>=0.5\,m </m> on actual giraffe
            </p>
            <p>
                To find the length, we set up the proportion:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 1 \,cm =\amp 0.5 \,m</mrow>
                    <mrow> ?=\amp 3 \,m</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{ 3 \,m \times 1 \,cm}{0.5 \,m} </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp  6 \,cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The height of the giraffe model is <m>{\color{blue} 6 cm}</m>.
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
               Kemmy drew a blueprint of his living room using a scale of <m>1:50</m>. If the actual length of the living room is <m>6 \,meters</m>, 
               what is the length of the living room on the blueprint?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The information provided in the question are,
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Scale: <m>1:50 </m> (which means <m>1\,cm</m> on the plan represents <m>50\,cm</m> in real life).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Actual length of the garage: <m>6 \,meters.</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We need to find the length of the garage on the plan.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since <m>1\, \text{ meter} = 100 \, \text{centimeters}</m>, we convert <m>6\, meters</m> to centimeters:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 1\,m=\amp 100 \, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow> 6\,m =\amp \frac{6\,m  \times  100 \, cm}{1\,m}</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 600\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, applying the scale:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 1\,cm=\amp 50\,cm </mrow>
                    <mrow> ?=\amp 600\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{600\, cm \times 1\,cm}{50\,cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 12 \,cm </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The length of the living room on the blueprint is <m>{\color{blue}12 \,cm }</m>.
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>
    


